I Don't Air

Plane Crashes: An Analysis on Fatalities¶

Whenever a plane crashes it is always on the news. The fear of flying is so common that even people who aren't afraid of flying get worried whenever strong turbulance hits. Despite not being common it is commonly shown in media, through shows, movies, and books to build build plot and setting. But in real life the first information people want to know about is how many fatalities there were. So the question is how fatal are plane crashes and have improvements made flying safer. Let's take a look at the planes crashes from 2000 - 2021 and see if flying has gotten safer over the years and are there any trends we can learn from?

First, we need some methods for scraping the data from http://www.planecrashinfo.com/database.htm

First we scrape the data. We take the table and take all the elements to create our observations. We want to separate some of the data. For example, some observations have a date but not a time.

  • date : date the plane crashed
  • year : year the plane crashed
  • timePlane : time the plane crashed
  • city : city the plane crashed
  • country : country the plane crashed
  • operator : airline for the plane, includes military operators
  • flightNum : flight number of the plane
  • depart : departure city
  • arrive : arrival city
  • ACType : air craft type
  • registration : registration
  • certificationNum : certification number
  • passengersAboard : number of passengers on board
  • crewAboard : number of crew on board
  • passengersDeath : number of passengers who died
  • crewDeath : number of crew who died
  • groundDeath : number of people who died not aboard the aircraft
  • summary : summary of what happened upto and during the crash The database also includes a summary about how the plane crashed. If the summary contains certain words we can then infer the cause of the crash. For example, if the summary contains words pertaining to weather(storms, fog, visibility), we know that weather caused or partially caused the crash. This method of obtaining crash causes is not perfect, we found the classifying words by manually looking through summaries and selecting words or predicting good words.

Our crash cause categories include:

  • weather : weather based accidents
  • mechanical : mechanical failures in the plane
  • conflict : intentional damage or control taken from the plane, such as sabotage or hijacking
  • terrain : damage caused by the surrounding terrain
  • accident : malpractice when flying the aircraft

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def make_soup(url):
  time.sleep(.6)
  r = requests.get(url)
  soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'html.parser')
  return soup

# get all links that are for the years 2000s
def get_links(url):
    soup = make_soup(url)
    a_tags = soup.find_all('a', href=re.compile(r"2\d\d\d"))
    links = [urljoin(url, a['href'])for a in a_tags]  # convert relative url to absolute url
    return links

def get_tds(link):
    soup = make_soup(link)
    tds = soup.find_all('tr')
    if tds is not None:
      info = []
      for td in tds:
        info.append(td.text)

def get_txt(link):
    soup = make_soup(link)
    tds = soup.find_all('td')
    if tds is not None:
      info = []
      for td in tds:
        info.append(td.text)

urls = []
date = []
year = []

weatherCause = ['wind' ,'rain', 'weather', 'lightning', 'visibility', 'fog', 'hail', 'snow', 'typhoon', 'hurricane', 'storm']
mechanicalCause = ['engine', 'fail', 'pressure', 'fire', 'flame']
conflictCause = ['shot', 'hijack', 'deliberate', 'sabotage', 'homemade', 'improvised', 'missle']
terrainCause = ['mountain', 'cliff', 'slope', 'tree', 'forest', 'Mt.', 'powerline']
accidentCause = ['accident', 'mistake', 'prerequisite', 'disorient', 'disregard', 'procedure', 'checklist']

def containsCause(summary, causes):
  for i in causes:
    if i in summary:
      return True
  return False

Now we can start scraping the website. Once we scrape the website, we need to clean it up as we have some missing data. We fill any missing times with pd.NaT and other missing values with pd.NA and some with None.

for i in range(22):
  urls.append(website + f"/{2000 + i}/{2000 + i}.htm")

us_states = ['Alabama', 'Alaska', 'Arizona', 'Arkansas', 'California', 'Colorado', 'Connecticut', 'Washington DC', 'Delaware', 'Florida', 'Georgia', 'Hawaii', 'Idaho', 'Illinois', 'Indiana', 'Iowa', 'Kansas', 'Kentucky', 'Louisiana', 'Maine', 'Maryland', 'Massachusetts', 'Michigan', 'Minnesota', 'Mississippi', 'Missouri', 'Montana', 'Nebraska', 'Nevada', 'New Hampshire', 'New Jersey', 'New Mexico', 'New York', 'North Carolina', 'North Dakota', 'Ohio', 'Oklahoma', 'Oregon', 'Pennsylvania', 'Rhode Island', 'South Carolina', 'South Dakota', 'Tennessee', 'Texas', 'Utah', 'Vermont', 'Virginia', 'Washington', 'West Virginia', 'Wisconsin', 'Wyoming']

for i in range(22):
  plane = get_links(urls[i])
  time.sleep(1)
  for p in plane:
    time.sleep(1)
    data = pd.read_html(p)[0][1]

    date.append(datetime.strptime(data[1], '%B %d, %Y') if '?' not in data[1] else pd.NaT)
    if date[-1] != pd.NaT:
      year.append(date[-1].year)
    data[2] = ''.join(filter(str.isdigit, data[2]))
    # add back ? if places becomes None 
    if not data[2]:
      data[2] = '?'

    timePlane.append(datetime.strptime(data[2], '%H%M') if '?' not in data[2] else pd.NaT)
    loc = data[3].split(', ')
    if len(loc) == 1:
      loc = data[3].split(' ,')
      if len(loc) == 1:
        loc = [loc[0], loc[0]] # for manicupality
    city.append(loc[0])

    if loc[1] in us_states: # places in USA have state instead of country name
          country.append('United States of America')
    else:
      country.append(loc[1])
    operator.append(data[4])

    flightNum.append(data[5] if '?' not in data[5] else pd.NA)
    depArr = data[6].split(' - ')
    
    # some places have route as 'Sightseeing'
    if len(depArr) == 1:
      arrive.append(depArr[0])
    else:
      arrive.append(depArr[1])
    depart.append(depArr[0])
    ACType.append(data[7])
    registration.append(data[8])
    certificationNum.append(data[9])

    m = re.search('passengers:(\d+) crew:(\d+)', data[10])
    if m:
      passengersAboard.append(int(m.group(1)))
      crewAboard.append(int(m.group(2)))
    else:
      passengersAboard.append(pd.NA)
      crewAboard.append(pd.NA)

    m = re.search('passengers:(\d+) crew:(\d+)', data[11])
    if m:
      passengersDeath.append(int(m.group(1)))
      crewDeath.append(int(m.group(2)))
    else:
      passengersDeath.append(pd.NA)
      crewDeath.append(pd.NA)

    if data[12] == '?':
      groundDeath.append(pd.NA)
    else:
      groundDeath.append(int(data[12]))

    summary.append(data[13])

    weather.append(containsCause(data[13], weatherCause))
    mechanical.append(containsCause(data[13], mechanicalCause))
    conflict.append(containsCause(data[13], conflictCause))
    terrain.append(containsCause(data[13], terrainCause))
    accident.append(containsCause(data[13], accidentCause))

Our first point of interest is with which is the leading cause of plane crashes? We can see that weather and mechanical causes are the leading cause of plane crashes. Let's take a closer look at this by graphing the number of fatalities these both contribute throughout the years.

totalDeathsYear = []
proportionDeaths = []
for d, a in zip(groupYear['passengersDeath'], groupYear['passengersAboard']):
  totalDeathsYear.append((np.sum(d[1]), d[0]))
  aboard = 1 if np.sum(a[1]) == 0 else np.sum(a[1])
  deaths = 0 if np.sum(a[1]) == 0 else np.sum(d[1])

  proportionDeaths.append((deaths/aboard, d[0]))
x, y = zip(*totalDeathsYear)
plt.plot(y, x)
plt.title('total deaths in plane crashes by year')
plt.ylabel('Total deaths')
plt.xlabel('Year')

crashes = []
frameCountry = frame.groupby(['year'])
years = list(range(2000,2022))
for i in frameCountry['passengersDeath']:
  crashes.append(len(i[1]))

plt.plot(years, crashes)
plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical')
plt.title('total crashes each year 2000-2021')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Crashes')
plt.show()

As we can see from the graph, there is an overall downward trend of total deaths in plane crashes per year. Although there are spikes due to tragic accidents, the overall trend is negative. We can attribute this to a multitude of things, such as:

  • The introduction of the Pilot Fatigue Rule (https://www.cnn.com/2011/12/21/travel/pilot-fatigue-rule/index.html#)
  • Mandating Locked cockpit doors after 9/11 (https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-32070528)
  • GPS Systems improving (https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/twenty-years-gps-and-instrument-flight)

from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim

geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="my_user_agent", timeout = 5)

location = []
for row in frame.itertuples():
  city = row[3]

  if "Near" in row[3]:
    city = row[3].replace("Near ", "")

  if "Off" in row[3]:
    city = row[3].replace("Off ", "")

  place = f"{city}, {row[4]}"
  loc = geolocator.geocode(place)
  if loc:
    location.append((loc.latitude, loc.longitude))
  else:
    # couldn't find location, approximate to just country
    loc = geolocator.geocode(row[4])
    if loc:
      location.append((loc.latitude, loc.longitude))
    else:
      location.append(None)

frame.insert(loc = 1, column = "lat long", value = location)

Let's give a different color for each year and lets scale the size of a circle around the crash location based on the number of fatalities for that crash. Let's also make a distinction between flights that departed in the country (white) and those outside the country (black). Many of these countries aren't just flying cargo or passanger planes but also doing military traning. Earlier we say that some military forces accounted for many plane deaths. So, let's also make a distinction between military and non-military planes with the color of the mark: military (white) and non-military (black).

def mapCrashes(mapSpot, year, lat, lon, fatal, domestic, military):
  colorMark = ['#ff3733', '#3375ff', '#33ff7c', '#8933ff', '#ffa133', '#cb4b4b', '#f29999', '#eecda9', '#0f165c', '#07610a', '#5f9ea0', '#3f0761', '#ffffff', '#f8b0e6', '#b0f2f8', '#b0f8cc', '#aeb7b2', '#000000', '#e0dbdb', '#efdf40', '#3b7d7c', '#8f81fd']
  colorBor = "#000000"
  if domestic:
    colorBor = '#ffffff'
  folium.CircleMarker(
    location=[lat, lon],
    radius= 1 * fatal,
    popup= str(year),
    color= colorBor,
    fill=True,
    fill_color=colorMark[2021 - year],).add_to(mapSpot)
  folium.Marker(location=[lat, lon],icon=folium.Icon(color = military, icon_color= colorMark[2021 - year])).add_to(mapSpot)

  if table['depart'] == 'Training':
    domestic = True
  military = 'black'
  if ('Military' in table['operator']):
    military = 'white'
  mapCrashes(map_osm5, int(year), float(coord[0]), float(coord[1]), table['passengersDeath'], domestic, military)

military = []
def isMilitary(operator):
  if operator is None:
    return False
  elif 'Military' in operator:
    return True
  else:
    return False

for index, table in frame.iterrows():
  military.append(isMilitary(table['operator']))


frame.insert(loc = 1, column = "military", value = military)

frameCountry = frame.groupby(['year', 'military'])
milDeaths = []
nonMilDeaths = []

for i in frameCountry['passengersDeath']:
  if i[0][1]:
    milDeaths.append((np.sum(i[1]), i[0][0]))
  else:
    nonMilDeaths.append((np.sum(i[1]), i[0][0]))
In [ ]:
mil = []
nonmil = []
years = []
for i in milDeaths:
  mil.append(i[0])
  years.append(i[1])
for i in nonMilDeaths:
  nonmil.append(i[0])


plt.plot(years, mil)
plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical')
plt.title('total fatalities for military planes 2000-2021')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('fatalities')
plt.show()

plt.plot(years, nonmil)
plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical')
plt.title('total fatalities for non-military planes 2000-2021')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('fatalities')
plt.show()

Based on the graphs, the fatalities for military deaths follow no trend. However, civilian fatalities seem to decrease over the years, this makes sense as the regulations we listed above seem to only affect commercial aircrafts. The reason for seperating planes between military and non-military is because when the average person thinks about plane accidents they are thinking about passenger planes or cargo planes. Military planes serve different purposes and it's not a type of plane that is accessible to everyone.

Conclusion¶

After looking at different aspects of plane crashes, we think it is resonable to say planes have indeed gotten safer throughout the years. We can also see that technological improvements and new regulations have lead to fewer crashes as evidenced in the articles linked previously. Since we only have data of plane crashes, we don't get to see all the planes that don't crash but we can infer that on average air travel has increased due to globalization and the increasing wealth of middle class citizens in countries with emerging air travel markets.

When we took a look at the most fatalities for plane crashes, we see a lot of developing countries pop up such as Nigeria, Iran, Indonesia, and even Russia (considered a developing country by the IMF and UN). This is cause for concern for airline operators, as their numbers will only continue to grow as the air travel market expands bigger as the countries become more developed.

When it comes to something tragic like an airplane crash, it's easy to put blame on one particular cause or another. However, from this analysis and across all our metrics: location, weather, operator, terrain, or even conflict, we can conclude that there simply is not a leading cause for plane crashes. We also see that once a plane crashing the outcome is unpredictable. Like for your health, prevention and safety measures for plane crashes is the best medicine.

Lasty, there are still some factors that this analysis does not consider and there are also some limitations from the data we have analyzed. Some factors missing are the planes that don't crash, this would help in figuring out the likelyhood of these crashes given their factors compared to planes that don't crash with similar factors. There were also some limitations such as only looking at 2000-2021, maybe looking at previous years would help build an argument in the trends discussed. There was also some limitations in missing data which lead to assumptions which could affect our analysis.
